   <font class="ArticleSource"><big>News Roundup:</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleHead"><big>Happy new year!</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </font><font class="ArticleAuthor">Coray</font>
   <div align="right">
   <font class="ArticleTime">12/31/2003 09:25 AM CST &nbsp;&nbsp; 77 Comments</font>
   <div align="left">
   <font class="ArticleText">Have you ever thought about why when you start up many MMOGs, you have to accept an End User Licensing Agreement (EULA), when any other software you get, pretty much never displays it? I thought EQ was bad and then I recently started up DAOC to find it asks for your CD key (luckily it remembers it), and then soon after, you have to press accept to both a EULA and a Rules of Conduct display, that the first time you see them, you are forced to scroll down before you can accept. It's the one area in the game where scroll bars work like you might expect.<p>Well one of the biggest fears for these companies has come true, in China atleast, where a player, won <a href="http://www.cnn.com/2003/TECH/fun.games/12/19/china.gamer.reut/index.html" target="_new">a court fight</a> to reclaim items lost to another player in-game. The meanings and issues here are far reaching, and while it has yet to be tested in the US courts, it's virtually inevitable that it will be at some point, and it's not as cut and dry as the EULA might try to sound.<p>The first thing to consider is the EULAs themselves. Contrary to what you might think, the things contained in these are not necessarily law, just because you agree to them. If Sony or some other company, put in, that if you ever talked bad about them on a website, they would send Ninjas to your house and cut off your hands, and I agree to it, that doesn't make it legal for them to send their ninjas to chop off my hands. <p>Many parts of the EULAs probably have been tested in courts, and would continue to stand up to tests, but to my knowledge, the concept of virtual ownership of game content has not been tested in the US, and until that time, it's anyones guess what would occur.<p>Now, what about the idea that players own anything in game? The view the companies take is that you are simply paying for access, and items are and remain theirs. In most cases the relevant information is stored on their computer, although I'm not sure how much that matters.<p>For example, a unique work, such as a piece of music is still the property of whoever wrote it, even in electronic form in someone elses possession. The space on your hard drive that contains those mp3s, belongs to you, but the specific set of information that can reproduce a copywritten work, belongs to whoever did it. The same arguement could be used in this case, that the space an item you make or find belongs to the company, it may be unique and created by you.<p>Look at a game like UO in the sense that it's merely a tool similar to Microsoft Word. When you open up word or, I open up frontpage and start to write out an article, Microsoft doesn't own what I type and the files I save, they couldn't come here and claim everything, and one could easily argue that many MMOGs are quite similar, in that works created within them, are copyright or belong to the person who made/had them.<p>Lastly, at this point it should go without saying that you could easily prove that in game items, have actual real life value which further complicates things.<p>Overall, the companies who have made and are making some of the future MMOGs are very afraid that these issues will be tested in US courts, and it's quite likely that any judge who sees such a case, would have little to no technical knowledge, which just adds insult to injury. There are compelling arguements on both sides, and if it went in favor of the player, it could be disasterous on the industry. In essence, the industry might cease to exist because of the costs involved with support and the like.<p><big>David vs Goliath</big><p>Next up in our day of legal battles, we have Mythic versus Microsoft. For some reason, Mythic, makers of DAOC, felt compelled to file a lawsuit against Microsoft because of their in development MMOG called Mythic<strong>a</strong>. I'm guessing that Mythic has in house lawyers who were just not busy enough because this is pretty absurd.<p>Honestly speaking if you had asked me a week ago, who made DAOC, I would have been at a loss. I doubt it's a coincidence that they felt the need to put out a press release about the entire thing. What probably annoyed me a bit more are comments made by Mark Jacobs, president of Mythic prior to this being done in relation to lawyers in his last state of the game update just 3 weeks or so ago...<p><strong>As required by lawyers everywhere, the usual disclaimer that this letter is a guide as to what we hope to do and not as a guarantee of any kind. I always hate saying this but that's what lawyers are for, to make us say things that we hate.</strong><p>In essence, the press release states that the name Mythica is too similar to Mythic as to confuse people. I guess, I just don't understand the purpose. I highly doubt anyone is going to get confused at all, or that it's going to impact either Mythic or the Mythica game, so it just seems pointless to me. <p><big>In other news</big><p>Lastly this time around we have some news on upcoming EverQuest updates.<p><strong>Melee Enhancement, part 2</strong><p><strong>Melee classes are currently enjoying the first part of the improved Melee system and the feedback we are receiving has been great. Early in 2004 we plan to move forward with the rest of the melee enhancement, the reaction abilities. The enhancement gives Monks, Rogues and Warriors the ability to use special skills in response to a mistake made by their opponent or an exceptional move of their own. This enhancement will be in addition to the existing system, allowing players to use the skills for more involved game-play and to improve the abilities of their characters.</strong><p><strong>A more detailed explanation and the transcript of a chat with the EQ Live team about the system can be found on the Developers Corner.</strong><p><strong>Graveyard Zone</strong><p><strong>Tired of losing your corpse? The current EQ system removes corpses from the game after a week to reduce clutter and potential video lag. But we know there are times when your character dies and you just can't get it right away. Next thing you know a day turns into a week and BAM! Your corpse is gone. Since we can't leave the corpses sitting in game indefinitely, some inventive folks here have come up with another option.</strong><p><strong>We plan to create a &quot;graveyard&quot; zone that will only work if your corpse has decayed and disappeared. If you have lost your corpse due to decay in other parts of Norrath, you will be allowed to enter this zone and reclaim it.</strong><p><strong>Tradeskill Interface Upgrade</strong><p><strong>Tired of all the clicking and dragging needed just to make a type 1 wood arrow? We know that the current tradeskill interface is cumbersome, so the UI guys have come up with some new ideas.</strong><p><strong>Opening a tradeskill container will now open a new user interface.&nbsp; In the window you will find an area that has all recipes that are currently available to you.&nbsp; This includes recipes that are at your skill level as well as some above it.&nbsp; Clicking on a recipe will display what items are necessary for its completion. Clicking the &quot;combine&quot; button will extract those required items from the player's inventory, and perform the recipe combine, placing the results on the player's cursor. The new system is nice and neat, with no dragging and dropping unless you want to&nbsp;try a combine that is way out of your league, which uses the old style of combination.</strong><p>I'm still hesitant about the additional melee changes because of issues I've mentioned before. I just doubt that it's going to work out well given the game and what we have received so far as far as endurance goes. To make a long story short, I see no reason to tie most or all of the skills to openings. No other class has to wait for a signal to pop up to use their abilities, why will pure melee? A problem example would be one of the openings allowing a warrior to use an ability to generate more hate from their attacks. What exactly are the chances of this opening coming up, when you actually require it? In the long run, even the good abilities will not often come up when you most need them and the net effect would be virtually no change except melee have to press buttons more often.<p>That's not to say you can't have abilities tied to openings, just that the critical ones, should NOT be tied to openings, or there should be seperate versions, one that you can use at any time, one that requires an opening, the difference being the endurance cost, with the anytime ability having a lot higher cost to use. So for example, that hate generating ability might have a 500 cost to use at any time, but only 250 on an opening. This changes things from being the whack a mole game that it's going to be where you basically press a button at a certain time, to where it's up to you to decide when you need to use things and what you need to use.<p>The graveyard zone idea, I assume that a lot of people have cited their own neglect as a reason for quitting the game, so in an effort to coddle them, instead of simply handling valid cases which I can't imagine are that numerous, they are making a zone for this. I just don't know what really to say here, it's not a bad idea really, but I'm just not sure why they would put resources on this and corpses are just going to be stacked to the roof because numerous players leave corpses with insignificant items around.<p>And the tradeskill interface, it's very cliche to even say this but sounds straight out of DAOC. In DAOC the menu displays everything you can make and even uses the consider colors so you pretty much know what to make, for the best skill gain. Overall it's fine with me to take the best ideas seen in other games, or the best ideas flat out and use them in your own game, so don't take it to mean that I'm slamming Sony for pretty much copying how DAOC does it. I guess I am a tiny bit bitter since I have already gotten my tradeskills at 220+ and all the changes to streamline things seem to occur well after I've fought my way through them. <p>Lastly it doesn't really fix the core problems with tradeskills, mostly the tedium of farming to gain skill, and how the vast majority of items you can make, are virtually useless.<br></font>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>
